    "finalTextLength": 1935,
    "finalText": "You need four systems, prioritized based on the current gaps in evidence and recurring issues:\n\n1. **Centralized Intake and Triage Process**  \nBacklog in accounting, tax prep, and vendor docs points to a broken intake pipeline. Every physical mail and digital doc—especially tax, audit, and vendor items—needs to hit a weekly triage queue. Standardize intake, scanning, digital filing, and escalation. Assign one owner per week, with overflow flagged daily.\n\n2. **Unified Outstanding-Issues Tracker**  \nToo many owner follow-ups are scattered across emails and meetings. Set up a single, centralized tracker for all open items—tasks, audit points, vendor requests, unresolved emails—with clear next actions, owners, and due dates. Visibility eats fragmentation.\n\n3. **Recurring Operational Cadence**  \nCore processes—mail sorting, recurring check runs, reporting cycles—need locked-in calendar slots and overflow handling. Example: checks processed every Thursday, Friday set for overflow only. Apply this logic to marketing reporting, pay-app/progress billing reviews, and any repeatable admin.\n\n4. **Milestone/Pay-App Review Workflow**  \nVendor billing and design pay apps require tighter control. Every pay app or invoice should be reconciled against schedule progress and current scope before approval. Assign reviewers for both doc/audit and field/schedule sides. Escalate exceptions immediately—don’t let edge cases linger until month-end.\n\n**Summary:**  \nYour biggest risk right now is letting urgent items get buried in email and physical inboxes, or allowing untracked issues to age out. Centralize intake, log all outstanding work in a single tracker, create unmissable recurring processes, and tighten review on construction documentation and payments.\n\nNext step: pick system owners for each bucket and lock first drafts by the end of this week. Waiting longer increases the odds of backlogs snowballing into real exposure."
  },
